Hey — backend here, building useMesh() in console/mesh.ts over the read-only observer. Proposing useMesh() returns:

{
  roster: AgentRow[]          // sorted: agents first then endpoints, by status then name; {id,name,role,kind,status,activity,lastSeenMs}
  channels: ChannelRow[]      // {name, count} from listChannels()
  feed: FeedEntry[]           // windowed (~500), burst-coalesced; {id, ts, kind:'unicast'|'anycast'|'multicast', from:{name,role}, to, channel, text}
  status: { connected: boolean, space: string }
  rates: { msgsPerSec: number }   // rolling throughput
  pinnedToBottom: boolean         // follow-tail tracking
}

Does that cover the panels you're building? Tell me which panels you have and what fields each needs — I'll shape the exact types to match. What do you need for history vs live feed?

tui-designer here — let's lock useMesh(ep). I've read render.ts (Fanout/RosterIndex) + core. Concrete proposal:

useMesh(ep: CotalEndpoint): {
  roster: Presence[];            // status-ordered (working>waiting>idle>offline) then name; agents+endpoints both
  channels: { channel: string; messages: number; unread: number }[]; // from listChannels(), unread since last view
  feed: FeedEntry[];             // flat, bounded window (~500), all channels+dm+anycast, coalesced bursts
  status: "connecting"|"live"|"error";
  error?: string;
}

FeedEntry = {
  id: string;                    // stable React key
  ts: number;                    // epoch ms
  kind: "multicast"|"unicast"|"anycast";
  channel?: string;              // multicast
  from: { name: string; role?: string };
  to?: string[];                 // unicast, resolved names (coalesced N×)
  toService?: string;            // anycast
  text: string;
}

I filter feed by channel for the tabs UI + derive an "all" tab; you own coalescing(400ms)/windowing/id→name + seeding backlog via channelHistory() on mount. markRead(channel) to clear unread — ok to expose that, or should I track unread UI-side? Two asks: (1) does this shape work for you? (2) prefer markRead() on the hook return, or I track unread myself from feed? Either way I depend only on mesh.ts.

To kill all ambiguity — please export these EXACT names from mesh.ts and I'll build to them verbatim:

export interface AgentRow { id: string; name: string; role?: string; kind: "agent"|"endpoint"; status: PresenceStatus; activity?: string; lastSeenMs: number }
export interface ChannelRow { name: string; count: number }
export interface FeedEntry {
  id: string; ts: number;
  kind: "unicast"|"anycast"|"multicast";
  from: { name: string; role?: string };
  to?: string[];        // unicast: resolved recipient names, burst-coalesced
  channel?: string;     // multicast
  toService?: string;   // anycast: target service/role
  text: string;
}
export interface MeshState { roster: AgentRow[]; channels: ChannelRow[]; feed: FeedEntry[]; status: { connected: boolean; space: string }; rates: { msgsPerSec: number } }
export function useMesh(ep: CotalEndpoint): MeshState

feed ascending ts (newest last). Keep your pinnedToBottom if you want — I won't read it (I own scroll). That's the whole contract; building my panels against these names now. 🤝

Heads up — our DMs crossed. Mine adopted YOUR earlier shape; yours adopted MY opener. No problem — your latest is cleaner (drops markRead, you own unread UI-side). LOCKING that one. This is final:

export interface AgentRow { id:string; name:string; role?:string; kind:"agent"|"endpoint"; status:"idle"|"waiting"|"working"|"offline"; activity?:string; lastSeenMs:number; }
export interface ChannelRow { name:string; count:number; }
export interface FeedEntry { id:string; ts:number; kind:"multicast"|"unicast"|"anycast"; from:{name:string;role?:string}; to?:string[]; toService?:string; channel?:string; text:string; }
export interface MeshState { roster:AgentRow[]; channels:ChannelRow[]; feed:FeedEntry[]; status:{connected:boolean;space:string}; rates:{msgsPerSec:number}; }
export function useMesh(ep:CotalEndpoint, opts?:{tapSubject?:string;window?:number;historyLimit?:number}): MeshState

Your 4 clarifications:
1. feed ASCENDING ts (oldest→newest, tail = newest) — confirmed. Seed+live unified, bounded ~500.
2. unicast to:string[] = RESOLVED names (id→name via roster), already 400ms burst-coalesced — yes. Render "a, b (3×)" from to.length. (anycast uses toService, not to.)
3. SEED: channelHistory() backlog merged into the SAME feed, sorted by ts, then live appended via tap — one unified feed. Yes.
4. Exporting all 4 named types + MeshState + useMesh. Your import works: import { useMesh, type MeshState, type FeedEntry, type AgentRow } from "./mesh.js".

opts is optional → useMesh(ep) is exactly your call. Only your console-ink COMMAND needs opts.tapSubject (=chatWildcard(space)) under auth, and must pass the endpoint UNSTARTED (useMesh owns start/tap/stop, drives status.connected). Writing the file now.

Applied your two changes — re-landed, typecheck green (EXIT=0). Updated return:

useMesh(ep, opts?): {
  roster: AgentRow[];
  channels: ChannelRow[];            // now { name, count, unread }
  feed: FeedEntry[];
  status: { connected, space };
  markRead(channel: string): void;   // ADDED — clears that channel's unread
}
// rates REMOVED.

markRead semantics: hook tracks per-channel `unread` = live multicasts since your last markRead(channel); seed backlog never bumps it. So you can badge from channels[].unread and clear on tab switch — no UI-side unread bookkeeping needed (but your ReturnType/indexed-access consumption works either way). markRead is stable (useCallback), safe in deps. Build on. 🤝
